Kurtosis and standardization¶

In [234]:
def standardization(x):
    return (x- np.mean(x))/np.std(x)

def kurtosis(x):
    return np.mean(np.power(standardization(x), 4))-3

# Creating X_patch which would be of (9, 39204) dimension

def build_matrix(dat_matrix, conv_filter):
    dat_matrix = dat_matrix/255

    width = len(dat_matrix[0])
    height = len(dat_matrix)

    convolution_matrix = []
    for i in range(0, height - conv_filter.shape[0] + 1):
        for j in range(0, width - conv_filter.shape[0] + 1):
            inner_matrix = []
            for row in range(j, j + conv_filter.shape[0]):
                for col in range(i, i + conv_filter.shape[1]):
                    inner_matrix.append(dat_matrix[col][row])
            convolution_matrix.append(inner_matrix)

    convolution_matrix_1 = np.array(convolution_matrix)

    convolution_matrix_transpose = convolution_matrix_1.transpose()
    return convolution_matrix_transpose

# store the value in the convolution_matrix
convolution_matrix = build_matrix(sgx_train, conv_filter)

Creating log and derivative function¶

In [267]:
def log_function(x):
    return 1/(1+np.exp(-x))

def log_derivative(x):
    return log_function(x)*(1- log_function(x))

Computing Gradient descent¶

We are going to use below formula to update our filter so that we can reach the local minima

$\partial E/\partial f= -2X{(s^T- g(f^TX)) \odot {g}'(f^TX)}/N$

$\Delta f(i) = -\partial E/\partial f(i)$

$f(i+1) <-f(i) +\alpha \Delta f(i)$

In [268]:
# iterating over 20000 times 

mse = []
for i in range(0,20000):
    FX = np.dot(conv_filter1.T, convolution_matrix)

    # log function and derivative of it
    log_array = log_function(FX)
    log_der_array = log_derivative(FX)

    # calculation S - g(FX) 
    Error = sg_train2.T- log_array
    
    #calculate mean squared error
    mse1 = np.mean(np.square(Error))
    mse.append(mse1)
    
    #multiply by first derivative
    Error_derv= np.multiply(Error,log_der_array)

    # calculation of dE/df
    dE_dF = -2*np.dot(convolution_matrix, Error_derv.T)/(198*98)

    # at 0.1 learning rate 
    conv_filter1 = conv_filter1 - 0.1*dE_dF

For calculating the hessian matrix we need to calculate v,p,u and G from the below functions¶

In [305]:
def v_calculation(itr):
    if itr == 0:
        pass 
    else:
        return(del_f[itr] - del_f[itr-1])

def p_calculation (itr):
    if itr == 0:
        pass 
    else:
        return(filter_upd[itr] - filter_upd[itr-1])


def u_calculation (itr,v,p,G):
    if itr == 0:
        pass 
    else:
        return(p/np.dot(p.T,v) - np.dot(G,v)/np.dot(np.dot(v.T,G),v))


def g_calculation (itr,v,p,u,G):
    if itr == 0:
        return(0.1*np.identity(9))
    else:
        return(G + np.dot(p,p.T)/np.dot(p.T,v) - np.dot(np.dot(G,v),np.dot(v.T,G))/np.dot(v.T,np.dot(G,v)) + np.dot(v.T,np.dot(G,v))*np.dot(u, u.T))

Running the loop for 300 times. Even though it converges very fast¶

In [309]:
mse_bfgs = []
filter_upd = []
filter_upd.append(conv_filter2)
del_f = []


for i in range(0,300):
    
    FX = np.dot(conv_filter1.T, convolution_matrix)

    # log function and derivative of it
    log_array = log_function(FX)
    log_der_array = log_derivative(FX)

    # calculation S - g(FX) 
    Error = sg_train2.T- log_array
    
    #calculate mean squared error
    mse1 = np.mean(np.square(Error))
    mse_bfgs.append(mse1)
    
    #multiply by first derivative
    Error_derv= np.multiply(Error,log_der_array)

    # calculation of dE/df
    dE_dF = -2*np.dot(convolution_matrix, Error_derv.T)/(198*198)
    del_f.append(dE_dF)
    
    # updating v,p,u and G
    v = v_calculation(i)
    p = p_calculation(i)
    u = u_calculation(i,v,p,G)
    G = g_calculation(i,v,p,u,G)
    
    
    conv_filter1 = conv_filter1 - np.dot(G,dE_dF)
    filter_upd.append(conv_filter1)

Creating a DFT matrix¶

In [4]:
def DFT_mat(N):
    Mat = np.empty((N,N), dtype = complex)
    for n in range(0,N):
        for f in range(0,N):
            Mat[n][f] = np.exp(-1j*(2*np.pi*n*f/N))
    return Mat

  1. Prepare your data matrix X. You extract the first frame of N samples from the input signal, and apply a Hann window2. What that means is that from the definition of Hann window, you create a window of size N and element-wise multiply the window and your N audio samples. Place it as your first column vector of the data matrix X. Move by N/2 samples. Extract another frame of N samples and apply the window. This goes to the second column vector of X. Do it for your third frame (which should start from (N + 1)th sample, and so on. Since you moved just by the half of the frame size, your frames are overlapping each other by 50%. (Note: this time its okay to use the toolbox to calculate Hann windows.)

Creating Inverse DFT matrix¶

In [31]:
# inverse DFT matrix
def DFT_mat_inv(N):
    Mat = np.empty((N,N), dtype = complex)
    for n in range(0,N):
        for f in range(0,N):
            Mat[n][f] = np.exp(1j*(2*np.pi*n*f/N))
    return Mat/N

# assigning the values of DFT inverse
DFT_inv = DFT_mat_inv(N)

  1. You multipy this matrix to your spectrogram, which is with suppressed white noise, to get back to the recovered version of your data matrix, X . In theory this should give you a real-valued matrix, but youll still see some imaginary parts with a very small value. Ignore them by just taking the real part. Reverse the procedure in 1.6 to get the time domain signal. Basically it must be a procedure that transpose every column vector of X and overlap-and-add the right half of t-th row vector with the left half of the (t + 1)-th row vector and so on. Listen to the signal to check if the white noise is suppressed.

If you load the images, they will be a three dimensional array of 381 430 3, whose third dimension is for the three color channels (RGB). Lets call them XL and XR. For the (i,j)-th pixel in the right image, XR , which is a 3-d vector of RGB intensities, we can scan and find the most similar pixel in the left image at i-th row (using a metric of your choice). For example, I did the search from XL to XL , to see which pixel among the 40 are(i,j,:) (i,j +39,:)the closest. I record the index-distance of the closest pixel. Lets say that XL is the (i,j +19,:)most similar one to XR . Then, the index-distance is 19. I record this index-distance (to (i,j,:) the closest pixel in the left image) for all pixels in my right image to create a matrix called disparity map, D, whose (i, j)-th element says the index-distance between the (i, j)-th pixel of the right image and its closest pixel in the left image. For an object in the right image (e.g. the tree), if its pixels are associated with an object in the left image, but are shifted far away, that means the object is close to the cameras, and vice versa.

Calculating Disparity matrix¶

In [99]:
Dis_mat = np.ones((im_left.shape[0],im_left.shape[1]-40))

for height in range(0,im_left.shape[0]):
    for width in range(0,im_left.shape[1]-40):
        #initialize some random value to calculate the minimum
        cost_int = im_left.shape[0]*1000
        
        for x in range(0,40):
            cost_fun = np.mean(np.square(im_right[height,width] - im_left[height,width+x]))
            if cost_fun < cost_int:
                cost_int = cost_fun
                Dis_mat[height,width] = x

Calculating the centroids¶

In [89]:
sub_mat = np.zeros((Dis_mat_flat.shape[0],Dis_mat_flat.shape[1]))
centroid = np.array([random.uniform(min(Dis_mat_flat),max(Dis_mat_flat)) for _ in range(4)], dtype = float)
centroid1 = np.zeros(4,dtype = float)

print(f'Initial centroid {centroid}')
for l in range(0,100):
    
    for i in range(Dis_mat_flat.shape[0]):
         sub_mat[i] = np.argmin(np.abs(Dis_mat_flat[i]- centroid))
            
    for j in range(len(centroid1)):
        centroid1[j] = np.average(Dis_mat_flat, weights = (sub_mat == j))
          
    if np.array_equal(centroid,centroid1):
        print(f'k-means has converged at iteration# {l}.')
        break
    
    centroid = copy.deepcopy(centroid1)
    print(f'At iteration {l} centroid value {centroid}')
